This document has the processing of the posterior data of the model from my master thesis. For technical reasons, I’m treating data on R, exporting and running the model on Matlab (something about the Wishart implementation on R that I couldn’t solve) and then importing back again to R in order to produce some graphs and tables. Sorry about the mess.

Plotting everything together

Impulse response analysis

I’m using the functions from the bvarsv package, which implements (Primiceri 2005) TVP-VAR model. I addapted some stuff to accept my inputs from Matlab and some functionalities (specifically, the other ways to compute the IRF) are not currently being used. The codes are available here and I’m following the documentation in (Krüger 2015).

Auxiliary Functions

# Auxiiary function 
# So the beta at time t is a vector with 21 entries
# The first M entries are the intercepts
# What this function does is to organize the vector into a matrix M x 1 + M*p
# The first column has the intercepts
# The next columns have the coefficients for each variable, for the first lag and then for the second lag and so on
beta.reshapes <- cmpfun(function(beta, M, p){
  auxa <- matrix(rep(NA, length(beta)), nrow = M)
  auxa[1:M] <- beta[1:M] # Intercepts in the first column
  for (pp in 1:p){  # Fills auxa M columns at each iteration
    auxa[, ((pp-1)*M+2):(pp*M+1)] <- t(matrix(beta[(M+1+(pp-1)*(M^2)):(pp*(M^2)+M)], nrow = M)) # each line is one equation of the VAR, in order
  }
  return(auxa)
})


# Another auxiliary function
multmat <- cmpfun(function(mat, mult) {
  
  if(mult == 0){
    out <- diag(nrow(mat))
  } else if (mult == 1) {
    out <- mat
  } else {
    out <- mat
    for (c in 1:(mult-1)) out <- out %*% mat # for each period you multiply the matrix by itself, like in Koop's code
  }
  
  return(out)
  
})


# Another auxiliary function
FIRmats <- cmpfun(function(A, H.chol = NULL, nhor, orthogonal = TRUE) {
  # Dimensions
  M <- nrow(A) #it is the same M as before, don't know why redoing
  
  # AR matrices
  
  p <- ncol(A)/M # This is not an integer, so I'm not sure how this works. It will always be slighter higher than the real p.
  
  # Construct companion form matrices
  
  if (p > 1){
    
    # VAR matrices
    
    Ac <- matrix(0, M*p, M*p)
    Ac[1:M, ] <- A
    Ac[-(1:M), 1:(M*(p-1))] <- diag(M*(p-1))
    
  } else {
    
    Ac <- A
  }
  
  
  # Matrix with impulse responses
  # A matrix with rows equal to the number of variables and columns equal to the number of horizons multiplied by the variables
  Phi <- matrix(0, M, M*(nhor+1))
  for (s in 0:nhor){
    aux <- multmat(Ac, s)[1:M, 1:M]
    if (!is.null(H.chol)) aux <- aux %*% H.chol
    Phi[, (s*M+1):((s+1)*M)] <- aux
  }
  Phi
})


FIR <- cmpfun(function(fit, impulse.variable = 1, response.variable = 2, tempo = NULL, nhor = 20, scenario = 2) {

# Get coefficient draws (this part I need to pay attention to get the same thing from the Matlab)

# Using Primiceri's data, this is 21 lines (parameters) x 153 columns (periods) * 5000 repetitions
# The object is an array
# If we have 3 equations and 2 lags, this means that each equation has 7 parameters. The problem is to figure out their order, if it is per equation or per variable

################################
Beta.draws <- fit$Beta.draws   #
################################

nd         <- dim(Beta.draws)[3] # Number of repetitions

if(is.null(tempo)) tempo <- dim(Beta.draws)[2] # If the period to compute the IRF is not informed, then use the last period available

out <- matrix(0, nd, nhor + 1) # It is a matrix to store the IRF values

M <- fit$M # number of VAR equations
p <- fit$p # number of lags

# Get information from the VCV matrix
# I'm not sure who is H and who is A

# H.draws is 3 x 459 x 5000, where 459 is 153 x 3 (the number of time periods multiplied by the number of var variables)
# H.sel is a synmetric matrix, so I don't think it is Sigma, but by reading the help on the IRF, I think it is Sigma :|
#H.sel is 3, 3, 5000, so my guess here is that it takes all the replications from the time t of the variance in the measurement equation

H.sel <- fit$H.draws[,((tempo-1)*M+1):(tempo*M),]

# A.draws must be the same dimension H.draws
# A.sel is a superior triangular matrix, with the elements of the diagonal equal to one
# A.sel is 3, 3, 5000 and I have the same hypothesis as the H.sel, but I'm not sure if it is the covariance in the state transition equation

#A.sel <- fit$A.draws[,((tempo-1)*M+1):(tempo*M),] 
A.sel <- NULL

if (scenario == 3){ # uses the average to compute the IFR
  # Compute mean of sigma over both time and MCMC draws, as made by Primiceri
  sig <- apply(exp(0.5*fit$logs2.draws), 1, mean)
  sig <- diag(sig)
} else {
  sig <- NULL
}

# Compute the impulse-response for each MC iteration

for (j in 1:nd){
  
  # Cholesky of VCV matrix, depending on specification
  if (scenario == 1){ # No orthogonalization at all
    H.chol <- NULL
  } else if (scenario == 2) {# Standard orthogonalization
    H.chol <- t(chol(H.sel[,,j]))
  } else if (scenario == 3) {# Orthogonalization as in Primiceri
    H.chol <- t(solve(A.sel[,,j])) %*% sig
  }
  
  ### I NEED TO TAKE IRFmat FUNCTION and BETA RESHAPE FUNCTIONS
  
  aux <- FIRmats(A = beta.reshapes(Beta.draws[,tempo,j], M, p)[,-1], H.chol = H.chol, nhor= nhor)
      aux <- aux[response.variable, seq(from = impulse.variable, by = M, length = nhor + 1)]
      out[j,] <- aux
  
}

list(contemporaneous = out[,1], irf = out[,-1])

})
# Getting everything together in the same object 
fit <- list(1)
fit$Beta.draws <- Betas
fit$p <- p.
fit$M <- M.
fit$H.draws <- Todos_H

Computing the IRF

So, the technical details regarding the IRF computation can be seen here, but basically the IRF estimates the impact of an unitary shock of \(\varepsilon_t\). The elements from \(B_t\) and \(\Sigma_t\) at the measurement equation are kept fixed in their \(t\) values (which is indicated by the option scenario = 2. The ordering of the variables matters and must be justified on economic grounds. The graphs contains the 5%, 25%, 50%, 75% and 95% percentile lines, based on 10.000 posterior draws.
